Deployment stack (VidShield AI, per CLAUDE.md):
- Docker for packaging (frontend, backend, workers).
- AWS for deployment: ECS Fargate, ALB, CloudFront, RDS (PostgreSQL), ElastiCache (Redis), S3, SQS, Lambda, ECR.
- CI/CD: GitHub Actions, Terraform, AWS CDK.
- Monitoring: CloudWatch, Prometheus, Grafana, Sentry.
- All secrets via AWS Secrets Manager or env; local via `.env` (gitignored).

DevOps rules:
- Applications must be container-friendly and stateless where possible (backend and workers).
- Keep builds reproducible; use environment-driven configuration.
- Separate build-time config from runtime config.
- Add health checks for API and workers; ensure logs are structured and production-usable.
- Support observability: system logs, pipeline monitoring, latency, error tracking, usage analytics (see observability rule).

Docker expectations:
- Keep Dockerfiles clean and optimized; prefer multi-stage builds when useful.
- Avoid baking secrets into images; minimize image size where practical.

AWS expectations:
- Prefer managed services (ECS Fargate, RDS PostgreSQL, ElastiCache Redis, S3, SQS, CloudFront) per DEPLOYMENT.md.
- Use least-privilege IAM policies; make networking and environment assumptions explicit.
- Support observability via logs, metrics, and alarms; design for rollback-safe deployments.

CI/CD expectations:
- Run lint, tests, and build validation before merge/deploy.
- Keep deployment config version-controlled; use separate environments (e.g. dev, staging, prod via terraform environments).

Do not:
- Hardcode AWS resource IDs, RDS URLs, or OpenAI/S3/Pinecone secrets in code.
- Mix deployment-only hacks into application logic.
- Assume local-only paths or config in production code.
